narratives.question_text: Indicate the total number of hours per week (outside the classroom) you spent on this course:
comments: About 4 (between reading the assignments and meetings with my group and preceptor).

narratives.question_text: Looking back on this course, what is your overall assessment of the course:  What are its strengths and weaknesses, and in what ways might it be improved?
comments: need more time for data collection periodlectures on leadership and sustainability were not useful
Very time consuming, could be improved by allowing more time in the beginning of the semester to start work on group projects.
Great concept. But in practice, we don't know what we are doing. Not enough time spent on actual project. Not enough guidance.
Good overall. Some of the lectures weren't particularly helpful, but the project experience was worthwhile.

I love the fact that the course provides practical experience by allowing you to work with the community on health issues. I felt like I learn more this way, than learning just the theory behind it in a classroom setting.

narratives.question_text: Please evaluate the instructor of this course. What are the instructor's strengths and weaknesses, and in what ways might his or her teaching be improved?
comments: Instructor: Debbie Lee Humphries  Strengths- enthusiastic

Instructor: Debbie Lee Humphries  Dr. Humphries was very receptive to feedback and criticisms of the course the entire semester. You could tell that she valued the students' opinions and really wanted the course to be the best and as effective as possible.

narratives.question_text: If this course included instruction by a teaching assistant (TA), please evaluate the TA here. What are the strengths and weaknesses and how might their teaching be improved? (Specify name of the TA).
comments: Laena was extremely helpful as a TA
Eliza: Very hands off approach which was good and bad for our group
Eliza was great. She provided a lot of positive feedback on how to make our project better, and pointed out things that we should think about that we may not have originally thought about.

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize this course for a fellow student? Would you recommend it to another student? Why or why not?
comments: If you have the time and are interested in Community Health, go for it.
It's intense, you get thrown in with high expectations and little guidance. It's kind of a mess. I would take it if I could go back in time. But I did add it on my resume and it looks good.
Aclass that provides the opportunity to gain hands on experience working with a community organization on a health related issue.
